00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
And in order to do so I just want
to go back 125 years or so to give

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
you a feeling for what the
history of biology has been like,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.000
some of it, since the
end of the 19th century.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Just to give you a little flavor for
what can happen to biology if things

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
aren't done right. Charles
Darwin had a cousin named

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Francis Galton. He was
knighted by the Queen and

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:17.000
called Sir Francis Galton.
And he was an early pioneer in

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:21.000
statistics. And he coined
the term eugenics. And,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
as you may note, eugenics
is simply the science of

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
trying to use genetics
to bread better livestock,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
better plants, and ultimately
maybe to breed better human beings.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
And we humans have been doing
eugenics on plants and livestock for

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.000
at least 10,000 years. That
is to say we have continually

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
been selecting out the best of the
breed as the progenitors of the next

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
generation of the breed. And
in that way corn, which was

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
originally this large when it was
grown 5,000 years ago in Mexico,

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:00.000
the cobs have now become
this large and quite tasty.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
And all of that is through selective
breeding. But in the last half of

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
the 19th century, inspired
by Darwin and subsequently

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.000
by Mendel's work on Mendelian
genetics, a whole science of

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:17.000
eugenics grew up in this country
which included not only the

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.000
improvement in the quality of
livestock and plants but also

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:26.000
improvements in the gene pool
of humanity. There was a strong

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:31.000
conviction that genes were directly
responsible for all kinds of

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
physical traits, as well
as mental and psychological

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
traits. There was a
strong belief that some

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:45.000
races were superior and other races
were inferior because of genetic

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
gifts or genetic deficits. And
this included as well within

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:54.000
races, however one defined them,
different ethnic groups. There was

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
a firm belief that science could
ultimately solve a lot of social

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:04.000
problems including urban violence,
labor unrest, manic depression,

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:09.000
schizophrenia and even
mental retardation.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And the eugenicists, as
they came to be known,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:16.000
came to believe that the
problems of the world, alcoholism,

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
poverty, prostitution, criminality,
feeblemindedness, chess playing

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
ability, tendency to
commit industrial sabotage,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
that was big in the beginning of
the 20th century when the unions were

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
coming into power, they were
all associated with one or

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
another rather penetrant
Mendelian allele.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:38.000
A well known geneticist named
Davenport, who subsequently was

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
associated with an unnamed
university up Mass Ave.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
studied various ethnic groups and
races and concluded that on the

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
basis of genetics the Germans
ranked highest in quality such as

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
leadership, humor, generosity,
sympathy and loyalty.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Italians and Irish ranked
lowest in most of these traits,

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
he was lucky he survived in this
town since together Italians and

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Irish, I think encompass
70% of the population.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
British were lowest in two of
the traits. Irish were highest in

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:16.000
suspiciousness. Jews were
highest in obtrusiveness,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
whatever that is. And all of these
things were said to be genetically

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
templated. And so at the beginning
of World War I IQ tests were first

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
instituted in this country during
the draft in order to determine who

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
was genetically fit to serve
and who was below standard.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And using IQ tests, which
were implemented in great

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
numbers and throughout the
society in the 1920s, a well known

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
geneticist named Goddard
discovered that 80% of Jewish,

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Hungarian and Polish immigrants,
as well as Italian and Russian

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
immigrants were mentally
defective or feebleminded,

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:57.000
and that these traits, these
mental defects in 80% of these

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:01.000
groups were transmitted as
regularly and as surely as the color

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
of hair or eyes. I'm not
making up fairy tales now.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
I'm telling you what's happened in
our history. In the 1920s there was

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:16.000
a Eugenics Record Office in this
country which existed for the next

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:21.000
twenty years, an American Eugenics
Society which has 1200 people,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.000
and J.H. Kellogg of Battle Creek,
Michigan, you know how he made his

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:30.000
money, don't you? Cornflakes.
He founded a Race Betterment

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:34.000
Association whose intent was to
better the gene pool of the American

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.000
population through selective
breeding. By 1928 there were 376

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
college courses taught across this
country on the subject of eugenics,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:46.000
i.e., how to improve the human
race by beginning to breed more

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.000
fit individuals. And so
when the Nazis came to power,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:55.000
as they did in 1933 in Germany,
they had much to draw from.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
In fact, most of their scientific
rationale, to the extent they had

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
any, didn't come from Germany,
it came from eugenicists in the

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.000
United States. And so
they began to look amongst

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:16.000
their society for people
who were useless eaters,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:22.000
i.e., they consumed food but didn't
produce, they lived lives not worth

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:27.000
living, the elderly, the
chronic poor, the crippled and

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:32.000
the misfits. And
they began involuntary

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:36.000
sterilization. So, people
who were regarded as

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
genetically less fit were sterilized.
By the time the Nazis finished

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
their 12 years in power, 400,000
people had been sterilized

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
in Germany because for one or
another reason they were regarded as

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
somehow defective. And as
the Second World War made

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
resources more tight, they
just did something much simpler,

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.000
they just euthanized people,
they just killed them if they were

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
regarded as in one way or
another genetically defective.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
In fact, my father had a first
cousin who around 1936 or so was

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
gassed because he had
a bad stuttering defect.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So, this is all things that
really happened to people.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:27.000
As a consequence of all of this
eugenics, by 1924 Immigration Act

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:32.000
was passed which severely
circumscribed the amount of people

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
immigrating into this country
because the immigrants were widely

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:42.000
viewed as diluting and
contaminating the American gene pool.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And this probably, well,
this undoubtedly had a

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
devastating affect on this country
which we'll never really be able to

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
know because the truth of the
matter is that to the extent we have

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
economic and scientific
robustness in this country,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
it has come, for the last century,
year after year, generation after

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.000
generation from the immigrants
who come to this country,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
not people who were here
three, four, five generations.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
It's the immigrants who
brought in the new ideas,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
the energy, the power, and I
venture to say that if I were

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
to ask what fraction of you are
first generation Americans the

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
number would be pretty high,
right? But in 1924 that was for a

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
while stopped simply because people
coming into the country were viewed

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:30.000
as genetically less
than acceptable.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:35.000
By 1940 thirty states had compulsory
sterilization laws in this country,

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:40.000
i.e., people who were deemed to
be genetically less gifted were

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.000
sterilized against their will.
60,000 of those sterilizations were

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:50.000
performed in this country. And
the eugenics moment gained more

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:55.000
and more adherence. What shut
it off ultimately was what

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
happened in World War II where
six million Jews were killed,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:03.000
along with probably five or six
million Slavs and other races who

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
were deemed, and gypsies, there
were probably half a million

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
gypsies killed by the Nazis,
different groups of people who were

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:15.000
deemed to be genetically less
deserving of living and genetically

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:20.000
less likely to be productive
and useful human beings.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
And were it not for World War
II, it's quite plausible that the

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:30.000
eugenics movement would have
continued to grow and that today,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:35.000
when we talk about genetics, much
of it would be referred to a belief

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
that somehow we can determine
people's phenotype and genotype and

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:45.000
that we can predict how useful or
useless they're going to be on the

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
basis of our insights into genetics.
And this ideology of genetic

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:55.000
determinism, I say it had a great
decline, this is the phrase we use,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:11:00.000
genetic determinism, i.e., to say
that an individual's life course is

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:05.000
strongly dictated
by his or her genome.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:08.000
These are her alleles. You
heard a lot about the alleles

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:12.000
last time from Eric. But
genetic determinism is once

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:16.000
again coming to the forefront.
Why? Because now, for the first

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
time, we actually have a
science of human genetics.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
When all of this other stuff was
going on 50 and 100 years ago it was

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:27.000
all pseudo-science, it was
all made up. No one had the

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
vaguest idea what genes
were present in people's DNA.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.000
They didn't even know about DNA.
They didn't really know about most

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Mendelian traits being
passed in human populations.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
And they had no way of knowing,
in the vast majority of cases,

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:46.000
whether a certain person's phenotype
was or was not dictated by genotype.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
So is this notion of a strong
genotype-phenotype connection

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
totally nonsense? Well,
I'll give you an example of

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
where you might begin to think it
isn't. And it comes from studies of

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
identical twins who were
separated at birth and brought up

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
in different families. So
these identical twins obviously

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
have an identical genotype.
So here's a famous story that I

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
like to refer to. There
was a chance meeting in 1979

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
between a steelworker named Jim
Lewis and a clerical worker named

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
Jim Springer. They both lived
in Ohio. They were separated five

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.000
weeks after birth and they were
raised 80 miles apart in different

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:27.000
towns in Ohio. And
at the age of 39 they

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
discovered themselves
through some change meeting.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
They discovered each other.
Well, they both had dark hair,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
they both stool six feet tall
and they both weighed 180 pounds.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:41.000
That's not so surprising. They both
spoke with the same inflections,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
which they clearly had not yet
learned to speak with when they were

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
five weeks old. They
walked with the same gait.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:51.000
They made the same gestures.
They both loved stockcar racing.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
They both hated baseball. They
both married women named Linda.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
They were both divorced and in
their second marriages both of them

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.000
married women named Betty.
They both drove Chevrolets.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:05.000
They drank Miller Lite. They
both chain smoked Salems.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
They vacationed on the same
half-mile of beach in Florida.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
They both had elevated blood
pressure, severe migraines,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.000
both had undergone vasectomies,
they both bit their nails, and their

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:19.000
heart rates, their brainwaves and
their IQs were so similar that you

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
couldn't tell whether it was the
same person or two separate people

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.000
being studied. Now, what
do you begin to think of

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.000
all that? Well,
that's an extreme case.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:35.000
The fact is most identical twins
raised apart do have a bit of

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:40.000
divergence in their phenotype,
in the way they grow up, but it

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:45.000
begins to plant in your mind the
notion that maybe many aspects of

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:50.000
the way we think and act actually
have a strong genetic template in

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:56.000
them. And one can begin to study
identical twins and ask things about,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:01.000
especially those who are separated
at birth, and not use such extreme

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:06.000
anecdotes like the one I just used.
And one begins to find that there's

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
an impressive list of attributes
that can only be explained by their

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.000
being a strong genetic determinant
in them. And these traits include

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:20.000
being alienated by people around one,
extroverted, being a traditionalist,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.000
looking backwards in terms
of one's customs, leadership,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:29.000
career choice, risk aversion,
attention deficit disorder,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:34.000
religious conviction and
vulnerability to stress.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:37.000
Heritability it turns out,
if you study identical twins,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:41.000
is about, I'm sorry, happiness,
if you study identical twins, is

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
about 80% heritable it turns out
and depends little on one's wealth,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.000
achievement or marital status. But
80% of it, if you study identical

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:53.000
twins, seems to have a genetic
template. And you'll say,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
well, that's all very satisfying,
but it begins to be a little

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:01.000
unsettling because it begins to
cause each of us to ask are we

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
really who we think we are or are we
just kind of cassette recorders who

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.000
are playing out the program that was
stuffed into us when the sperm hit

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:13.000
the egg that lead to each
of our appearing on the face

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.000
of the planet? To what
extent are we individuals or

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.000
to what extent are we simply
manifestations of genotype?

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
And to what extent do we have
freewill? That's kind of an

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:29.000
interesting question.
Now, people like Eric,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
I'm not pointing an accusing finger,
people like Eric have begun to

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
refine the science of genetics
so it really is a science.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.000
And so, restriction
fragment polymorphisms,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:44.000
SNPs, haplotype analysis are now
uncovering a staggering array of

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
human traits. I believe that the
number of human traits that have now

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
been localized, specific
genes, most of these are

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
diseased genes, exceeds
2,000 is my recollection.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
And there are only 21,000,
22,000 genes in the human genome.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
And the pace with which genes
and genotype and phenotype will be

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:06.000
linked to one another is going
to increase if nothing else.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.000
Many of the traits that one thinks
about in terms of human beings are

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:13.000
obviously polygenic. They're
not single strong Mendelian

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.000
alleles with strong penitence.
They represent the confluence,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:21.000
the collaboration of multiple
alleles that are conspiring to

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
create one or another phenotype.
And these polygenic traits or even

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
polygenic diseases have
traditionally resisted analysis

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:33.000
because mathematically they
are so complex to dissect out,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:37.000
to dissect out the contributing
genes which together as a cohort

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
create a genotype. But,
as Eric told you last time,

