across this planet?
Now, you will say to me,

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:27.000
well, God has made all his children
equal. But the fact is if you look

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:31.000
at the details of human evolution,
some of which I discussed with you a

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:36.000
week ago, last week, you'll
come to realize that most

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:40.000
populations in humanity are
the modern descendents of very

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:45.000
small founder groups. Remember
about the story of the Fins.

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:50.000
70% of Finish men carry the same
Y chromosome. All modern Fins,

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:55.000
most modern Fins, all of them are
likely to be the descendents of a

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:00.000
small founder group that
came into Finland 2,000 or 3,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:05.000
00 years ago and carry with them the
peculiar set of polymorphisms that

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:09.000
founder group happens to have had.
And arguments like that begin to

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:13.000
persuade you that there'll be
different allele frequencies in

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:17.000
different populations of humanity.
What if somebody begins to discover

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:21.000
that Macedonians have an enormously
high rate of the ability to play

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:25.000
chess because of a certain
allele? And here I'm talking very

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:29.000
speculatively. I'm not
literally meaning that.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:33.000
And Tibetans have a very poor
ability to construct software

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:38.000
programs because of a genetic allele
they carry? I hope nobody's Tibetan

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:42.000
here. I tried to choose two.
Are there any Macedonians? All

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:47.000
right. I succeeded. All
right. Anyhow. So the fact is

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:51.000
it's inescapable that different
alleles are going to be present with

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:56.000
different frequencies in different
inbreeding populations of humanity

00:34:56.000 --> 00:35:00.000
or populations of humanity that
traditionally have been genetically

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:05.000
isolated from one another. It's
not as if all the genes that we

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:09.000
carry have been mixed with everybody
else's genes freely over the last

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:13.000
100,000 years. Different
groups have breed

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:17.000
separately and have, for
reasons that I've told you,

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:21.000
founder affects and genetic
drift acquired different sets and

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:25.000
different constellations of alleles.
So what's going to happen then, I

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:29.000
ask you without wishing to hear an
answer because nobody really knows?

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:32.000
Then for the first time there could
be a racism which is based not on

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:36.000
some kind of virulent ideology,
not based on some kind of kooky

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:40.000
versions of genetics,
because the eugenicists in the

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:43.000
beginning of the 20th century, as
well as the Nazis hadn't had any

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:47.000
idea about genetics, they
were just using the word,

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.000
even though they knew nothing
about the science of genetics as we

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:55.000
understand it today. But
what happens if now for the

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:58.000
first time we, i.e., you
who begin to understand

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:02.000
genetics, begin to perceive
that there are, in fact,

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:06.000
different populations of humanity
that are endowed with different

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:10.000
constellation of alleles that we
imagine are more or less desirable?

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:13.000
What's going to happen then? I
don't know. But some scientists

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:17.000
say, well, the truth must come
out and that everything that can be

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:21.000
learned should be learned, and
we will learn how to digest it

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:25.000
and we will learn how to live with
that. But I'm not so sure that's

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.000
the right thing. And you
all have to wrestle with

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:32.000
that as well. And even
more insidious is the

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:36.000
following notion. Remember
the story about the two

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:40.000
Jims, the two guys from Ohio who met
one another at the age of 39 after

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:44.000
they'd been separated at five
weeks of birth? That story begins to

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:48.000
persuade you of something I said
before, and that is that a lot of

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.000
what you think you are isn't
what you made of yourself,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:56.000
isn't what your parents made
of yourself, isn't what your

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:00.000
environment made of you
and your experiences.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:04.000
Maybe it's all just in your genes.
And if that's so then maybe you

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:08.000
can't take credit for any of
the good things you've done.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:12.000
And conversely maybe you're not
responsible for all the bad things

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:16.000
you've done. Maybe three years from
now somebody will begin to plead

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:20.000
that even though they were
not criminally insane when they

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:24.000
committed a string of serial murders,
in fact it really wasn't their fault

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:28.000
because they happen to have this
particular genotype which is known

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.000
to be correlated with a
strong tendency to violent.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:35.000
And, by the way, there
is an allele which has a

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:39.000
correlation, I forget which one it
is, has a correlation with violent

00:37:39.000 --> 00:37:43.000
behavior. So what if one begins to
write off everything we do as not a

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:46.000
reflection of our own freewill,
our own volition, but instead a

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:50.000
consequence of the genes which
our parents hoisted on us?

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
Of course, we can blame it on them.
As a father of children, I can tell

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:58.000
you that it's amazing how many
different things can be blamed on

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:02.000
the parents. [LAUGHTER] Of
course, the parents have their

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:06.000
own out. The parents can
blame it on their parents.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:10.000
So now it goes back to the
grandparents, back to the beginning

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:14.000
of time. We laugh about these
things and they are amusing,

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:18.000
but they are taking us on a
collision course with some very

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:22.000
difficult problems. And you
guys have to wrestle with

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:26.000
them and you guys have to explain
to the people who haven't taken 7.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:31.000
12 where the world of
biology is taking us.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:35.000
And on that note, I want
to tell you that Eric and I

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:40.000
have enormously enjoyed
being with you this semester.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:44.000
We wish you much luck and
success in your future lives.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:49.000
We hope some of you have become
interested in biology and that you

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:53.000
found this course a little different
from what you took in high school.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:58.000
And have a wonderful winter
vacation. See you. [APPLAUSE]